Capstone project: Providing data-driven suggestions for HR¶

Description and deliverables¶

This capstone project is an opportunity for you to analyze a dataset and build predictive models that can provide insights to the Human Resources (HR) department of a large consulting firm.

Upon completion, you will have two artifacts that you would be able to present to future employers. One is a brief one-page summary of this project that you would present to external stakeholders as the data professional in Salifort Motors. The other is a complete code notebook provided here. Please consider your prior course work and select one way to achieve this given project question. Either use a regression model or machine learning model to predict whether or not an employee will leave the company. The exemplar following this actiivty shows both approaches, but you only need to do one.

In your deliverables, you will include the model evaluation (and interpretation if applicable), a data visualization(s) of your choice that is directly related to the question you ask, ethical considerations, and the resources you used to troubleshoot and find answers or solutions.

PACE stages

  • Plan
  • Analyze
  • Construct
  • Execute

Pace: Plan Stage¶

  • Understand your data in the problem context
  • Consider how your data will best address the business need
  • Contextualize & understand the data and the problem

Understand the business scenario and problem¶

The HR department at Salifort Motors wants to take some initiatives to improve employee satisfaction levels at the company. They collected data from employees, but now they dont know what to do with it. They refer to you as a data analytics professional and ask you to provide data-driven suggestions based on your understanding of the data. They have the following question: whats likely to make the employee leave the company?

Your goals in this project are to analyze the data collected by the HR department and to build a model that predicts whether or not an employee will leave the company.

If you can predict employees likely to quit, it might be possible to identify factors that contribute to their leaving. Because it is time-consuming and expensive to find, interview, and hire new employees, increasing employee retention will be beneficial to the company.

Familiarize yourself with the HR dataset¶

The dataset that you'll be using in this lab contains 15,000 rows and 10 columns for the variables listed below.

Note: you don't need to download any data to complete this lab. For more information about the data, refer to its source on Kaggle.

Variable Description
satisfaction_level Employee-reported job satisfaction level [0–1]
last_evaluation Score of employee's last performance review [0–1]
number_project Number of projects employee contributes to
average_monthly_hours Average number of hours employee worked per month
time_spend_company How long the employee has been with the company (years)
Work_accident Whether or not the employee experienced an accident while at work
left Whether or not the employee left the company
promotion_last_5years Whether or not the employee was promoted in the last 5 years
Department The employee's department
salary The employee's salary (U.S. dollars)

1. Stakeholders for this project is the HR department at Salifort Motors and company's senior leadership team.

2. The current high rate of turnover among Salifort employees that has been observed is the problem we are dealing with in this project. We will try to find and propose data-driven solution on how to improve employee satisfaction levels at the company and give the management the opportunity to predict employees likely to quit, or even to identify factors that contribute to their leaving. Since the procedure of finding, interviewing, and hiring new employees is time-consuming and expensive, increasing employee retention will be beneficial to the company.

3. We have a dataset with 15000 rows and 10 columns. There are both numerical and categorical variables. We have the "left" variable included that is going to be used as the target variable so we conclude that we have label data thus we will use the supervised ML classification techniques and methods.

4. The resources we used for this stage is the dataset from kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mfaisalqureshi/hr-analytics-and-job-prediction?select=HR_comma_sep.csv) and the information given in the "Description and deliverables" section of these assignment (https://www.coursera.org/learn/google-advanced-data-analytics-capstone/ungradedLab/uskOX/activity-course-7-salifort-motors-project-lab/lab?path=%2Fnotebooks%2FActivity_%2520Course%25207%2520Salifort%2520Motors%2520project%2520lab.ipynb) We also used python libraries pandas and seaborn, to load and manipulate the data and also visualise information.

5. We need to know if the information in the dataset is ethically acquired. This procedure need to be clear because the way it was performed may has resulted in introducing bias and unwanted false information in the dataset. We also need to check the "performance" variable and examine how it is calculated and if it is a fair process. Mistreatment or misjudjement of an employees performance can have great impact on the reasoning of quitting a job position. Finally we need to make sure that the inferences of our model will be used with caution and only in the benefit of an employee's status in the company. We need to make clear that a predictive model can and will have errors that have real-life concequences if applied without further consideration.

What did you observe about the relationships between variables?¶

From the correlation heatmap we can see that performance, number of projects, average monthly hours, are the most correlated with each other, tenure and satisfaction also are correlated with other variables.

What do you observe about the distributions in the data?¶

Satisfaction Level is a crucial variable in our case. We see a spike when satisfaction level is zero, which is expected. We also see two peaks with the highest at around 0.4 and a wider but lower in 0.8.

In performance evaluation we also see 2 peaks one at 0.5 and another wider in 0.8. This can mean that average performing employees left but high-performance employees also appear to be leaving the higher their performance is maybe because promotion rejection.

Number of projects also plays a role since we observed that the higher the projects the higher the probability of employee leaving. Additionally, in the lowest value of projects involved (2) we see high probability. There is an optimal value of number of projects which is 3.

Average monthly hours follows same distributions with satisfaction with an extend in higher values where every employee that worked in the extreme value has left the company.

We also see higher probability of leaving in the 5 year tenure employees.

Accident seems to be irrelevant with the results since there a not many employees that had accidents same with promotion. We can see that the higher the salary the lower the probability of an employee leaving.

Across department we see an equal probability distribution with lower values only in management and R&D departments

What transformations did you make with your data? Why did you choose to make those decisions?¶

We transform the categorical data with One Hot Encoding method to numerical variables since all our models work better with numerical variables.

What are some purposes of EDA before constructing a predictive model?¶

Clean the data. Check data type and validity Transform data to extract relevant and useful variables Check and remove missing values. Check and decide if needed to remove outliers. Check correlations between variables. Remove irrelevant variables of not significant importance.

Recall model assumptions¶

Logistic Regression model assumptions

  • Outcome variable is categorical
  • Observations are independent of each other
  • No severe multicollinearity among X variables
  • No extreme outliers
  • Linear relationship between each X variable and the logit of the outcome variable
  • Sufficiently large sample size

We are not going to use Logistic regression at his point¶

Do you notice anything odd?¶

In previous stage we identify the correlation between the variables and we selected the "left" column as the target predicted value. From the available columns only few appeared to have meaningful information. We decided to build simple Decition Tree Model and from that to extract the features with the highest importance to use in more advanced models later.

Which independent variables did you choose for the model and why?¶

From the before mentined Decision Tree the results as expected where that satisfaction, performance, projects, monthly_hours, tenure and if salary is low are the most important features. To minimize computational capacity needed for the more advanced models we decided to keep only this features.

Are each of the assumptions met?¶

Our Supervised ML methods do not have strict assumption we need to be aware of. Naive Bayes will use a Categorical algorithm which assumes all features are caterical and transform numerical data to such features. The independence among predictors and the equal power predictors assumptions may be violated but there is no need to focus on this matter since finally the more advanced models do not need to follow these rules.

How well does your model fit the data?¶

We build and test five models. Each was fitted using a random validation set and then all where tested in the same test set. The results , based on the f1 score, clearly show that the XGBoost tuned algorithm outperformed the others.

The results were: Accuracy: 98.266% Precision: 98.690% Recall: 90.763% F1: 94.561%

Can you improve it? Is there anything you would change about the model?¶

We have tried various model and fine tuned parameter so at this point the only way to improve the model is either with the addition of external new data, or with better feature engineering.

What resources do you find yourself using as you complete this stage? (Make sure to include the links.)¶

We used mainly the sklearn library and the various classifiers and test modules available.

Do you have any ethical considerations in this stage?¶

At this stage ethical considerations involce the correct interpretation of the results. Our model has very good results in precision, accuracy and f1 but the recall is lower than the other metrics. Recall is calculated from TP/(TP+FN) which mean that we have ~10% false negatives. This is when our model will predict that an employee is not going to leave the company(negative) but he will actually leave. This is very important to know that 10% of these situations cannont be predicted by our model. On the other hand, the insights provided here will help not only predict a similar situation but also improve the odds of such a situation never occur in the first place.

#Useful functions
#Create result DataFrame for each model and append total results
def make_results(name,y_val,y_pred):
    '''
    Accepts as argument model object name, y data (train or validate), and y data predictions.
    Prints the scores.
    Returns a dictionary with the score for this model to be appended in the results table.
    ''' 
    accuracy_ = accuracy_score(y_val, y_pred)
    precision_ = precision_score(y_val, y_pred)
    recall_ = recall_score(y_val, y_pred)
    f1_ = f1_score(y_val, y_pred)
    
    # Print scores
    print(name)
    print(f'Accuracy  :{accuracy_:>8.3%}')
    print(f'Precision :{precision_:>8.3%}')
    print(f'Recall    :{recall_:>8.3%}')
    print(f'F1        :{f1_:>8.3%}')

    #Append scores to results table
    results_ = {
        'Method': name,
        'Accuracy': accuracy_,
        'Precision': precision_,
        'Recall': recall_,
        'F1': f1_
    }
    
    return results_


#Confusion Matrix function that will be used for all models
def conf_matrix_plot(model, x_data, y_data):
    '''
    Accepts as argument model object, X data (test or validate), and y data (test or validate). 
    Returns a plot of confusion matrix for predictions on y data.
    ''' 
    model_pred = model.predict(x_data)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_data, model_pred, labels=model.classes_)
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm,
                             display_labels=model.classes_)
  
    disp.plot()
    plt.show()

pacE: Execute Stage¶

  • Share actionable steps with stakeholders

Recall evaluation metrics¶

  • AUC is the area under the ROC curve; it's also considered the probability that the model ranks a random positive example more highly than a random negative example.
  • Precision measures the proportion of data points predicted as True that are actually True, in other words, the proportion of positive predictions that are true positives.
  • Recall measures the proportion of data points that are predicted as True, out of all the data points that are actually True. In other words, it measures the proportion of positives that are correctly classified.
  • Accuracy measures the proportion of data points that are correctly classified.
  • F1-score is an aggregation of precision and recall.

What key insights emerged from your model(s)?¶

Satisfaction level is the most important feature in the dataset and and play a vital role to the decision of an employee leaving or staying with the company. This is not the only important feature. Heavy workload (number of projects and average monthly hours) lack of promotions despite high performance evaluation and low salary tend to contribute to the final decision.

What business recommendations do you propose based on the models built?¶

The company should prioritise the satisfaction of its employees and reduce workload when and if possible.

There is an optimal number of projects, 3, where after that value there is increased probability of an employee leave.

We observe also high turn rate after 4 years tenures. This can be due to the lack of promotions.

We see a clear correlation between high average monthly hours and high turn rate.

There is also high turn rate among employees with high performance evaluation again related probably to high monthly hours and lack of promotions.

What potential recommendations would you make to your manager/company?¶

Perform better satisfaction level evaluations. Assign every employee to a max of 3 projects. Retain average working hours at <250, optimally between 150-170 Increase promotions at 4 years tenure. Move high performance employees from the low salary category to higher paid positions.

Do you think your model could be improved? Why or why not? How?¶

The model can be improved but the overall performance will not provide any additional benefit or insights from those acquired with these models. The key point is to implement changes in the employee management procedures and improve satisfaction.

Given what you know about the data and the models you were using, what other questions could you address for the team?¶

We can discuss about what other feautures may be available from the company, or how we could feature engineer other more important and relevant that those already discussed.

What resources do you find yourself using as you complete this stage? (Make sure to include the links.)¶

This stage is part of the stakeholder management where visualizations and descriptive stats are crucial to give those interest in the results of the project clear view about the models capabilities and restrictions.

Do you have any ethical considerations in this stage?¶

At this stage we have concluded the model building evaluation and presentation to the stakeholders. We need to emphasise on the constrains of using such a model in predicting an employee decision and focus more on the insights of improving the features that the model recignised as the most important.
